es by embracing the strategies, cultures, and politics of each others' experiences. At the center of this study is the theory of spatial entitlement: the spatial strategies and vernaculars utilized by working class youth to resist the demarcations of race and class that emerged in the postwar era. In this important new book, Johnson reveals how racial alliances and antagonisms between Blacks and Chicanos in L.A. had spatial as well as racial dimensions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCommunity developmentzCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aMinoritiesxPolitical activityzCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistory. 0aMinoritieszCaliforniazLos AngelesxSocial conditions. 0aPopular musicxSocial aspectszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  a20th century.  aafrican americans.  aanti racist alliances.  ablack americans.  achicanos.  acultural expressions.  ahistorians.  ainstitutional repression.  ainterracial alliances.  alos angeles.  aminority communities.  amusic and culture.  amusic historians.  amusic history.  apostwar era.  apower imbalances.  arace and class issues.  arace issues.  aracial alliances.  aregional music.  asocial repression.  aspatial entitlement.  aspatial politics.  aus history.  aworking class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027528740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095485440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954854423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520954854/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY